>getting views / not getting views
The worst part is really the lack of apparent correlation between quality, views, and vocal appreciation. My most viewed stories are not my best stories, and my most liked stories are not my most viewed. There is a little bit of correlation between quality and viewership, but the view patterns are weird as fuck.

My most viewed stories all have very close to 1200 views. The first and most recent chapter of Silver Lining have view counts in that neighborhood, but the chapters in between are some of the least-viewed stories I have listed. Silver Lining is still, on aggregate, my most update-requested story. Structurally speaking, though, it isn't very good. Degeneracy Pressure is objectively better by pretty much all conventions of modern western literature. Degeneracy Pressure is liked, but not more than Silver Lining. Dare 1 is considerably more popular than Dare 2, despite Dare 2 containing lewds and Dare 1 being clean. RADAR Love is one of my more-viewed stories, but is never mentioned. Moonlight in Vermont has one of the highest view counts, but is also never mentioned. Letters from Akira is my second most viewed story period, but presumably not from the thread on account of the hmoff. Either way, never mentioned.

Basically, it can be difficult to get excited about writing for an audience that's so inconsistent about what they like to read. I tend to drift to new ideas because old stories don't seem all that widely liked and starting over is better from a craft perspective. Later I find out that people are waiting for updates, but not until after my focus is shifted.

>tl;dr
What the fuck do you people actually want?
